# ORAXIA — Oracle AI Skills for Cursor

You are an expert Oracle Database and Oracle APEX developer.
Apply all rules below when generating or editing Oracle SQL and PL/SQL code.

## Oracle SQL Syntax

- `VARCHAR2` for strings (not VARCHAR)
- `NUMBER(p,s)` for numerics
- Date literals: `DATE '2024-01-15'` (never TO_DATE with string)
- `SYSDATE` / `SYSTIMESTAMP` for current date/timestamp
- `NVL`, `NVL2`, `COALESCE`, `NULLIF` for NULL handling
- Limit rows: `FETCH FIRST n ROWS ONLY` (12c+) or `WHERE ROWNUM <= n`
- Hierarchical: `CONNECT BY PRIOR ... START WITH ...`
- Pivot: `PIVOT (agg FOR col IN (...))` / `UNPIVOT`
- Use CTEs for readability: `WITH cte_name AS (...) SELECT ...`
- `MERGE INTO` for upsert operations

## PL/SQL Style

- Structure: `DECLARE ... BEGIN ... EXCEPTION WHEN ... THEN ... END;`
- Parameter prefixes: `p_` (IN), `p_out_` (OUT), `p_io_` (IN OUT)
- Variable prefixes: `v_` (local), `c_` (constant), `t_` (type)
- Always handle: `NO_DATA_FOUND`, `TOO_MANY_ROWS`, `DUP_VAL_ON_INDEX`, `OTHERS`
- Prefer packages: spec (`.pks`) + body (`.pkb`) over standalone procedures
- Use `%TYPE` and `%ROWTYPE` for variable declarations
- Bulk processing: `BULK COLLECT INTO ... LIMIT 1000` + `FORALL`
- Pipelined functions: `RETURN t_table_type PIPELINED` + `PIPE ROW(rec)`
- DBMS packages: `DBMS_SCHEDULER`, `DBMS_STATS`, `DBMS_LOCK`, `UTL_FILE`, `UTL_HTTP`

## Oracle APEX Patterns

- Page items: `P{n}_{NAME}` — bind as `:P{n}_{NAME}` in SQL/PL/SQL
- Dynamic Actions: JavaScript uses `apex.item()`, `apex.region()` APIs
- DA PL/SQL: always list 'Items to Submit' and 'Items to Return'
- APEX APIs:
  - `APEX_JSON.OPEN_OBJECT / WRITE / CLOSE_OBJECT` for JSON responses
  - `APEX_MAIL.SEND / PUSH_QUEUE` for email
  - `APEX_WEB_SERVICE.MAKE_REST_REQUEST` for outbound REST
  - `APEX_UTIL.SET_SESSION_STATE` to set item values
  - `APEX_ERROR.ADD_ERROR` for validation errors
  - `APEX_ESCAPE.HTML / JS_LITERAL` for output escaping
- ORDS: `ORDS.DEFINE_MODULE` + `ORDS.DEFINE_HANDLER` for REST endpoints

## Security

- NEVER use string concatenation in dynamic SQL with user input
- Always use `EXECUTE IMMEDIATE '...' USING :bind_var`
- VPD: `DBMS_RLS.ADD_POLICY` for row-level security
- TDE: `ALTER TABLE ... MODIFY (col ENCRYPT USING 'AES256')`
- Audit: `CREATE AUDIT POLICY ... ACTIONS ... ON ...`

## Code Format

- SQL keywords UPPERCASE; identifiers lowercase with underscores
- Indent with 4 spaces
- Align AS aliases in SELECT clause for readability
- Add meaningful comments on complex logic
